System Upgrade and Setup:

1.  Setup a root account and secured it.
2.  From the root account, installed acl.
3.  Ran 'ip addr' and retrieved the IPv4 address. Then opened PowerShell
        on the Host machine and established a remote connection.  So, 
        I can act as root on the server and the user from the remote
        terminal.
4.  Created a file in the user directory from root, and added some text.
5.  From user ran 'ls -ltr' to check that the file was created. Then ran 
        'cat' for the file to read the content. Verified the content was present.
6.  From user attemted to add another line of text and received 'Operation
        not permitted' message.  This was expected.
7.  From root ran 'setfacl -m u:username:rw path/to/file' command to give read
        and write permissions to the user.
8.  Returned to the user ternimal and attempted to added text to the file again.
        Command was executed without issue.  Ran 'cat' on the file and verified
        the added text was present.
9.  From root checked for upgradable system files, and found 17.
10. Ran 'apt install upgrades' to install all upgrades to the system files. 
11. As root created another file with some text in the user directory.
12. As the user verified the file and content were present and attempted to add
        more content and was denied.
13. Ran 'sudo setfacl -m u:username:rw file'.
14. Then verified that the command worked by added more text to the file.